 Unfortunately for our universities, Performance Contracting (PC) has not only shifted from their main mandates, but also turned into a mere routine check.
For instance, you will find staff at universities struggling to fill endless reports in the name of compliance. Almost all government agencies are flocking these institutions, demanding that the latter account for what they have done towards achieving certain targets.





Corruption
The institutions have been turned into secretariats for PC reporting — on corruption, national cohesion, public complaints, drugs and substance abuse, disability mainstreaming, road safety, and what not.
Whereas these constructs make sense, the details required are far much removed from the core functions of the institutions.
It isn’t clear how the ritualistic reporting enhances the mandates of universities. Methinks the education sector adopted PC thoughtlessly. Whereas most universities are ISO certified, for example, their underperformance in key areas such as financial management and academics betray these bureaucratic ideals.
Online submission
QMS has worked well for production industry; but it may come a cropper if it is not well domesticated in education.



