A classic example is the current Teacher Performance and Appraisal Tool, which, on scrutiny, appears a vain exercise. Teachers collaborate to score themselves highly, and placate their employer’s ego through timely online submission of reports. 
It is high time that the institutions were allowed to narrow down to certain key performance indicators, so as to make it easy for them to stay focused.
As things stand, university leadership remains beholden to irrelevant performance indicators that earn them certification, yet the institutional output cannot be felt. Consequently, the whole certification process becomes a farce.
True certification needs to be reflected in the overall achievement of the core mandates of universities, with emphasis on their ability to proffer solutions to societal problems.
